Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:02.465
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:07.394 --> 00:00:08.560
ELLIE POWERS: Hey everybody.

00:00:08.560 --> 00:00:11.670
So I'm Ellie Powers from
the Google Play team.

00:00:11.670 --> 00:00:14.110
And thanks so much for cutting
your lunch a little bit

00:00:14.110 --> 00:00:17.340
short to make it back here.

00:00:17.340 --> 00:00:20.510
When I was 13 years old
and I was in middle school,

00:00:20.510 --> 00:00:21.650
we read this book.

00:00:21.650 --> 00:00:23.150
It was called "Lakota
Woman," and it

00:00:23.150 --> 00:00:25.450
was this really powerful
story of a woman who

00:00:25.450 --> 00:00:28.630
grew up in a Native American
reservation in South Dakota.

00:00:28.630 --> 00:00:31.270
The place looked like this,
a really beautiful place.

00:00:31.270 --> 00:00:33.795
But her story was completely
different from mine.

00:00:33.795 --> 00:00:35.420
She went through all
sorts of struggles

00:00:35.420 --> 00:00:36.990
that I'd never heard about.

00:00:36.990 --> 00:00:39.330
And we read this book as
part of our larger unit

00:00:39.330 --> 00:00:42.150
that we were doing on
Native American history.

00:00:42.150 --> 00:00:44.860
And in order to
graduate seventh grade,

00:00:44.860 --> 00:00:47.690
we had to complete a massive
independent research project.

00:00:47.690 --> 00:00:50.030
I'd never done anything
like it before.

00:00:50.030 --> 00:00:52.230
And after reading
her story I said,

00:00:52.230 --> 00:00:55.850
I have to do my presentation
on Native American religious

00:00:55.850 --> 00:00:57.680
freedom and oppression
in the United States

00:00:57.680 --> 00:01:00.240
in the second half of the 1900s.

00:01:00.240 --> 00:01:03.370
Because I was 13-year-old,
and I guess that's just what

00:01:03.370 --> 00:01:05.150
made sense to me at the time.

00:01:05.150 --> 00:01:07.780
So I went into the library.

00:01:07.780 --> 00:01:10.090
I had procrastinated
a bit, I do admit.

00:01:10.090 --> 00:01:12.610
So I tried to find books
that talked about the topic

00:01:12.610 --> 00:01:13.840
that I wanted to write about.

00:01:13.840 --> 00:01:16.110
And I really wanted to write
about individual stories

00:01:16.110 --> 00:01:18.950
of people who had
experienced oppression

00:01:18.950 --> 00:01:21.700
and had had struggles in
terms of being able to express

00:01:21.700 --> 00:01:23.153
their religious beliefs.

00:01:23.153 --> 00:01:26.416
And it wasn't so surprising,
looking back on it,

00:01:26.416 --> 00:01:27.790
that I couldn't
find these books.

00:01:27.790 --> 00:01:30.820
Because the information
was either too new, or it

00:01:30.820 --> 00:01:33.640
was too controversial
to be published.

00:01:33.640 --> 00:01:36.340
But luckily, I grew
up in Silicon Valley.

00:01:36.340 --> 00:01:38.620
So even though my life
was a little bit weird,

00:01:38.620 --> 00:01:41.750
it meant that I had some
tools that I could access

00:01:41.750 --> 00:01:43.530
that helped me do
a little bit more

00:01:43.530 --> 00:01:45.670
than I could have done
with my local library.

00:01:45.670 --> 00:01:48.810
I want to introduce
you to my SPARCstation.

00:01:48.810 --> 00:01:50.070
Anyone remember this computer?

00:01:50.070 --> 00:01:51.360
This was the first
computer that I

00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:52.850
had that could
access the Internet,

00:01:52.850 --> 00:01:54.900
and it was back
in the early '90s.

00:01:54.900 --> 00:01:57.490
And my family had
a Sun SPARCstation

00:01:57.490 --> 00:02:00.190
that looked almost
exactly like this.

00:02:00.190 --> 00:02:02.550
And this computer
was so awesome.

00:02:02.550 --> 00:02:05.330
Not only did it
have a CD-ROM drive,

00:02:05.330 --> 00:02:07.070
it also had a color screen.

00:02:07.070 --> 00:02:10.229
It didn't have Firefox,
because that didn't exist.

00:02:10.229 --> 00:02:12.220
But it had a three button mouse.

00:02:12.220 --> 00:02:13.620
You can't even
buy those anymore.

00:02:13.620 --> 00:02:14.780
I mean, three buttons.

00:02:14.780 --> 00:02:18.500
That's 50% more efficient than
most mice on the market today.

00:02:18.500 --> 00:02:23.440
And best of all, my
SPARCstation had a modem.

00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:25.320
And I was one of
the first people

00:02:25.320 --> 00:02:27.300
I knew who could
connect to the Internet.

00:02:27.300 --> 00:02:29.970
The Internet wasn't amazing
back then like it is today,

00:02:29.970 --> 00:02:31.270
and you couldn't do a lot.

00:02:31.270 --> 00:02:34.400
But this was my first
chance to find information

00:02:34.400 --> 00:02:36.970
that wasn't available
in my local library,

00:02:36.970 --> 00:02:40.720
and to reach out to people who I
would have never met otherwise.

00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:42.480
So when I was trying
to write my report

00:02:42.480 --> 00:02:44.820
and I couldn't find
any books, at first

00:02:44.820 --> 00:02:47.050
I thought I was
completely out of luck.

00:02:47.050 --> 00:02:50.725
But then I realized that
my SPARCstation had Mosaic.

00:02:50.725 --> 00:02:52.325
Do you remember Mosaic?

00:02:52.325 --> 00:02:54.410
Do you remember these
dark gray backgrounds?

00:02:54.410 --> 00:02:56.000
You remember them,
I can see that.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:57.870
Do you remember the blue
links, and when you clicked

00:02:57.870 --> 00:02:59.110
on them they turned purple?

00:02:59.110 --> 00:03:01.440
I mean, that was awesome, right?

00:03:01.440 --> 00:03:03.610
And I found Mosaic.

00:03:03.610 --> 00:03:05.430
I could cruise
around a little bit.

00:03:05.430 --> 00:03:08.152
And then, if you didn't have
Mosaic, maybe you had Gopher.

00:03:08.152 --> 00:03:09.110
Do you remember Gopher?

00:03:09.110 --> 00:03:11.109
It was like a lot of
folders, and you could just

00:03:11.109 --> 00:03:13.276
go from one folder, the
next folder, another folder.

00:03:13.276 --> 00:03:15.108
And sometimes you could
find images and text

00:03:15.108 --> 00:03:17.450
in those folders, and send
your folders to your friends,

00:03:17.450 --> 00:03:19.630
and tell them which
folders were the best.

00:03:19.630 --> 00:03:21.030
This was really cool.

00:03:21.030 --> 00:03:22.820
And it was through
these tools that I

00:03:22.820 --> 00:03:26.060
stumbled onto something amazing
that solved all of my problems.

00:03:26.060 --> 00:03:29.450
It was called NATCHAT,
Native American Chat.

00:03:29.450 --> 00:03:34.080
And basically this is where
historians and other people

00:03:34.080 --> 00:03:35.610
interested in Native
American issues

00:03:35.610 --> 00:03:37.820
would go to talk
about anything related

00:03:37.820 --> 00:03:39.510
to Native American culture.

00:03:39.510 --> 00:03:41.990
So I started hanging
out in NATCHAT.

00:03:41.990 --> 00:03:44.460
I got completely immersed
in a whole new world

00:03:44.460 --> 00:03:46.480
that I had never
even heard of before.

00:03:46.480 --> 00:03:49.570
I got all the information
that I needed for my project.

00:03:49.570 --> 00:03:52.240
I interacted with new
people who had nothing to do

00:03:52.240 --> 00:03:54.050
with my regular everyday life.

00:03:54.050 --> 00:03:56.290
And I wrote my report.

00:03:56.290 --> 00:03:58.330
Not only did I write
my report, but I

00:03:58.330 --> 00:03:59.990
included all this
information I'd

00:03:59.990 --> 00:04:02.900
learned from people that no one
in my school had learned about.

00:04:02.900 --> 00:04:06.990
And I felt that I was able
to educate not only myself,

00:04:06.990 --> 00:04:09.090
but also my teachers
and other students.

00:04:09.090 --> 00:04:11.540
I felt so powerful.

00:04:11.540 --> 00:04:13.557
And I said, this is great.

00:04:13.557 --> 00:04:15.140
I've accomplished
something important,

00:04:15.140 --> 00:04:17.959
and I want everyone else to
have the same experience.

00:04:17.959 --> 00:04:20.480
So, of course--
remember, I was 13--

00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:22.830
I taught my little siblings
how to use the computer.

00:04:22.830 --> 00:04:25.090
I wanted them to have
that feeling too.

00:04:25.090 --> 00:04:28.210
And that was cool, but
that wasn't enough either.

00:04:28.210 --> 00:04:31.470
I wanted everyone to have
this great experience,

00:04:31.470 --> 00:04:33.520
this feeling of connectedness.

00:04:33.520 --> 00:04:36.147
And I thought, yup, sooner
or later, everyone's

00:04:36.147 --> 00:04:38.230
going to have their own
SPARCstation just like me,

00:04:38.230 --> 00:04:40.120
and this is going to be awesome.

00:04:40.120 --> 00:04:43.907
But looking back, this
was never going to happen.

00:04:43.907 --> 00:04:45.740
It wasn't going to be
possible that everyone

00:04:45.740 --> 00:04:47.490
could have a SPARCstation.

00:04:47.490 --> 00:04:49.630
If you look at the technology
that we have today,

00:04:49.630 --> 00:04:52.360
it's so different from
that SPARCstation.

00:04:52.360 --> 00:04:53.930
Let's do a couple comparisons.

00:04:53.930 --> 00:04:57.060
So this SPARCstation, with its
awesome three button mouse,

00:04:57.060 --> 00:04:58.540
thousands of dollars.

00:04:58.540 --> 00:05:01.320
An Android One phone, which
is basically a supercomputer

00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:03.720
in comparison, less than $100.

00:05:03.720 --> 00:05:06.690
Obviously a huge benefit.

00:05:06.690 --> 00:05:09.544
Do you guys remember
learning touch typing?

00:05:09.544 --> 00:05:10.960
Mavis Beacon, and
you had to learn

00:05:10.960 --> 00:05:13.670
how to press all those little
buttons in the right order?

00:05:13.670 --> 00:05:15.900
That was actually hard,
looking back on it.

00:05:15.900 --> 00:05:17.959
And today we have touch
screens and sensors.

00:05:17.959 --> 00:05:19.500
They're so simple
that you don't even

00:05:19.500 --> 00:05:21.041
have to teach young
kids how to start

00:05:21.041 --> 00:05:22.460
using a phone or a tablet.

00:05:22.460 --> 00:05:24.980
They just figure it out.

00:05:24.980 --> 00:05:27.440
Back then, you had
your big SPARCstation

00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:28.370
stuck on your desk.

00:05:28.370 --> 00:05:30.240
There were tons of
wires coming out of it.

00:05:30.240 --> 00:05:33.320
If the power ever went out,
you lost all your work.

00:05:33.320 --> 00:05:35.790
But today, you can connect
anywhere in the world.

00:05:35.790 --> 00:05:38.060
You can charge a phone
wherever you can.

00:05:38.060 --> 00:05:39.630
It's so much better.

00:05:39.630 --> 00:05:42.460
And this is great, because
back in the day only

00:05:42.460 --> 00:05:44.940
a couple of super nerds could
connect to the Internet,

00:05:44.940 --> 00:05:46.780
and I didn't think
that was fair.

00:05:46.780 --> 00:05:49.170
I wanted all super nerds
to connect to the Internet.

00:05:49.170 --> 00:05:52.300
In fact, I wanted everybody
to connect to the Internet.

00:05:52.300 --> 00:05:55.010
And so this ability
to give people

00:05:55.010 --> 00:05:57.710
the same powerful feeling
of connectedness and access

00:05:57.710 --> 00:06:01.030
to information is actually
why I'm at Google.

00:06:01.030 --> 00:06:03.510
I'm really excited to be
here because Google's mission

00:06:03.510 --> 00:06:05.060
to organize the
world's information

00:06:05.060 --> 00:06:06.980
and make it
universally accessible

00:06:06.980 --> 00:06:09.390
is so deeply tied to
what's important to me,

00:06:09.390 --> 00:06:12.000
and what has made a
difference in my own life.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:13.590
And so what Google
Play is, is it's

00:06:13.590 --> 00:06:15.330
what happens when
we've connected now,

00:06:15.330 --> 00:06:17.130
literally, a billion people.

00:06:17.130 --> 00:06:19.595
And we've given them access
to a connected catalog

00:06:19.595 --> 00:06:21.300
of experiences.

00:06:21.300 --> 00:06:23.930
And that catalog, and those
connected experiences,

00:06:23.930 --> 00:06:27.400
are made possible by
developers like all of you.

00:06:27.400 --> 00:06:31.100
And so now here we are, at
this special moment in history.

00:06:31.100 --> 00:06:33.050
Developers can
have a huge impact

00:06:33.050 --> 00:06:35.360
on both local and
global problems,

00:06:35.360 --> 00:06:37.020
because everyone's
connected now.

00:06:37.020 --> 00:06:39.060
And a lot of that
is through Android.

00:06:39.060 --> 00:06:42.970
So I want to tell you a story
of some of these developers.

00:06:42.970 --> 00:06:46.300
Our first story takes
us to Sao Paulo, Brazil.

00:06:46.300 --> 00:06:49.099
And "Emprego Ligado" means
"jobs online" in Portuguese.

00:06:49.099 --> 00:06:50.640
We actually have a
couple people here

00:06:50.640 --> 00:06:53.314
from the Emprego Ligado team
today, which is pretty awesome.

00:06:53.314 --> 00:06:54.730
And they're proud
to say that they

00:06:54.730 --> 00:06:57.680
have made the number
one blue collar jobs

00:06:57.680 --> 00:06:59.890
service in all of Brazil.

00:06:59.890 --> 00:07:03.070
So let's learn a little bit more
about why this is important.

00:07:03.070 --> 00:07:08.170
So Sao Paulo is home to 11.8
million people, and the worst

00:07:08.170 --> 00:07:12.020
traffic jams in the world,
according to Time Magazine.

00:07:12.020 --> 00:07:14.550
So Emprego Ligado
saw this common pain

00:07:14.550 --> 00:07:18.290
point, this commute time in
Sao Paulo, it's just painful.

00:07:18.290 --> 00:07:19.990
I mean, three hours.

00:07:19.990 --> 00:07:23.869
That is a long time to spend
commuting every single day.

00:07:23.869 --> 00:07:25.410
And the most common
way to get around

00:07:25.410 --> 00:07:26.826
there is actually
on a public bus.

00:07:26.826 --> 00:07:30.120
There's about 16,000
buses in Sao Paulo.

00:07:30.120 --> 00:07:31.780
These buses are
often overcrowded.

00:07:31.780 --> 00:07:33.520
It can be hard to get a seat.

00:07:33.520 --> 00:07:35.370
And three hours a
day is a long time

00:07:35.370 --> 00:07:39.444
to spend your life sitting on
a bus, or standing on a bus.

00:07:39.444 --> 00:07:40.860
And so this is
some of the traffic

00:07:40.860 --> 00:07:42.800
that you'll be spending
your time sitting through.

00:07:42.800 --> 00:07:44.591
Luckily, it's a beautiful
city, and it even

00:07:44.591 --> 00:07:46.710
has some cool murals to look at.

00:07:46.710 --> 00:07:48.810
But I mean, that's just
a lot of your life.

00:07:48.810 --> 00:07:51.210
And so Emprego Ligado
had a key insight.

00:07:51.210 --> 00:07:53.010
Let's say we compare two people.

00:07:53.010 --> 00:07:56.717
One person has this crazy
three hour daily commute.

00:07:56.717 --> 00:07:58.550
Another person has a
more reasonable commute

00:07:58.550 --> 00:08:00.109
of around one hour per day.

00:08:00.109 --> 00:08:01.650
So if you do the
math, that basically

00:08:01.650 --> 00:08:03.566
it means that the person
with the long commute

00:08:03.566 --> 00:08:07.950
is wasting 20 business days
of their life commuting.

00:08:07.950 --> 00:08:10.790
That's time when they're
not economically productive,

00:08:10.790 --> 00:08:12.860
they can't earn money,
they can't spend time

00:08:12.860 --> 00:08:14.780
with their family,
and it's creating

00:08:14.780 --> 00:08:18.320
a huge financial and
psychological impact on them.

00:08:18.320 --> 00:08:21.330
So Emprego Ligado was
founded back in 2012

00:08:21.330 --> 00:08:23.170
by three college friends
who are incredibly

00:08:23.170 --> 00:08:24.870
passionate about
Latin America and went

00:08:24.870 --> 00:08:26.790
to live and work there.

00:08:26.790 --> 00:08:28.540
Not only did they
see this problem,

00:08:28.540 --> 00:08:30.740
that people were spending
a lot of time commuting,

00:08:30.740 --> 00:08:32.870
and that that wasn't very
fun-- and actually, that

00:08:32.870 --> 00:08:34.750
was leading to the
traffic problems

00:08:34.750 --> 00:08:37.200
in the big cities of Brazil
getting worse and worse.

00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:39.950
But also, employees had
an extremely inefficient

00:08:39.950 --> 00:08:40.824
recruiting process.

00:08:40.824 --> 00:08:42.990
And it was hard for them
to find the right employees

00:08:42.990 --> 00:08:44.610
for their companies.

00:08:44.610 --> 00:08:47.590
So the job market was
really broken, actually.

00:08:47.590 --> 00:08:49.730
Job seekers had
no way to find out

00:08:49.730 --> 00:08:51.420
about new jobs that
were available.

00:08:51.420 --> 00:08:53.690
So, if you had a
job, you would just

00:08:53.690 --> 00:08:55.470
stick it out, until
maybe you happened

00:08:55.470 --> 00:08:56.470
to hear about something.

00:08:56.470 --> 00:08:58.040
Maybe your friend tells you.

00:08:58.040 --> 00:08:59.850
But until then, you were stuck.

00:08:59.850 --> 00:09:02.750
And employers were
really struggling too.

00:09:02.750 --> 00:09:05.990
They needed to find people
with the right experience.

00:09:05.990 --> 00:09:08.660
And the commute time was the
top reason that a lot of people

00:09:08.660 --> 00:09:09.230
left jobs.

00:09:09.230 --> 00:09:12.530
There was a survey,
actually, that 37%

00:09:12.530 --> 00:09:15.630
of people who were earning
a kind of low to middle wage

00:09:15.630 --> 00:09:17.580
in the region, said
that they had actually

00:09:17.580 --> 00:09:19.480
left a job due just to traffic.

00:09:19.480 --> 00:09:21.660
No other reason,
just their commute.

00:09:21.660 --> 00:09:25.420
And so imagine, if you had 37%
of your workforce potentially

00:09:25.420 --> 00:09:27.200
leaving their job
at your company,

00:09:27.200 --> 00:09:29.190
and you'd have to replace
them, just because

00:09:29.190 --> 00:09:30.660
of the commuting situation.

00:09:30.660 --> 00:09:32.615
I mean, that's tough.

00:09:32.615 --> 00:09:34.240
And so they calculated
that-- let's say

00:09:34.240 --> 00:09:37.310
we have a company with
about 100,000 employees.

00:09:37.310 --> 00:09:39.240
So you could be losing
up to $80 million

00:09:39.240 --> 00:09:43.090
a year due to employee turnover,
because of these retention

00:09:43.090 --> 00:09:45.176
and recruitment difficulties.

00:09:45.176 --> 00:09:46.800
But not only did they
see this problem.

00:09:46.800 --> 00:09:50.780
They also saw an opportunity
to increase transparency

00:09:50.780 --> 00:09:52.255
in the job market.

00:09:52.255 --> 00:09:53.630
So they looked at
the job market.

00:09:53.630 --> 00:09:55.560
And these are the most
common jobs in Brazil.

00:09:55.560 --> 00:09:58.330
So you have, you could be
a waiter in a restaurant,

00:09:58.330 --> 00:10:02.350
maybe you drive a truck,
maybe you're a contractor,

00:10:02.350 --> 00:10:05.160
maybe you work as an
assistant in a shop.

00:10:05.160 --> 00:10:07.880
And in fact, these
types of jobs represent

00:10:07.880 --> 00:10:10.800
85% of the entire
Brazilian workforce.

00:10:10.800 --> 00:10:15.100
And so they decided to focus
on these types of jobs.

00:10:15.100 --> 00:10:17.270
And these not only were
the most popular jobs,

00:10:17.270 --> 00:10:20.865
but also here the information
transparency was the poorest.

00:10:20.865 --> 00:10:22.240
So this was really
an opportunity

00:10:22.240 --> 00:10:24.990
to have a hugely broad impact.

00:10:24.990 --> 00:10:27.520
Often you'd find
out a worker could

00:10:27.520 --> 00:10:29.680
have had a similar job in
their local neighborhood,

00:10:29.680 --> 00:10:31.570
but they just had
no way to find it.

00:10:31.570 --> 00:10:34.180
Imagine how frustrating
that would be.

00:10:34.180 --> 00:10:36.760
So let's talk about
the type of person

00:10:36.760 --> 00:10:39.560
who Emprego Ligado
is able to help.

00:10:39.560 --> 00:10:42.830
So Fernanda, if we drew her
as an Android-ified cartoon,

00:10:42.830 --> 00:10:44.170
would look like this.

00:10:44.170 --> 00:10:47.590
And so she's got
a cool pink suit.

00:10:47.590 --> 00:10:50.930
And she'd been unemployed for
about three and a half weeks

00:10:50.930 --> 00:10:52.860
when she signed up
for Emprego Ligado.

00:10:52.860 --> 00:10:55.180
And this time had been
really stressful for her.

00:10:55.180 --> 00:10:56.920
She had a family
who depended on her,

00:10:56.920 --> 00:10:58.680
and they needed her support.

00:10:58.680 --> 00:11:00.639
And she also used to
have a long commute.

00:11:00.639 --> 00:11:02.180
And with a city full
of supermarkets,

00:11:02.180 --> 00:11:04.513
you'd think it should be easy
for her to find a new job.

00:11:04.513 --> 00:11:08.380
But unfortunately, she
hadn't had any luck.

00:11:08.380 --> 00:11:11.140
So when Emprego Ligado
got started in 2012,

00:11:11.140 --> 00:11:13.700
they built a full
featured job search system

00:11:13.700 --> 00:11:15.660
using just text messaging.

00:11:15.660 --> 00:11:18.110
So think about the last
text message that you sent.

00:11:18.110 --> 00:11:23.080
Maybe it was like, LOL,
OMG, or a couple of emoji.

00:11:23.080 --> 00:11:26.020
Now imagine that you are
using the same system

00:11:26.020 --> 00:11:29.420
to find qualified
workers meaningful jobs

00:11:29.420 --> 00:11:30.690
in their local area.

00:11:30.690 --> 00:11:32.620
So this is a big
usability challenge

00:11:32.620 --> 00:11:33.870
that they managed to overcome.

00:11:33.870 --> 00:11:35.286
So I want to walk
you through what

00:11:35.286 --> 00:11:37.090
Fernanda did with the system.

00:11:37.090 --> 00:11:39.410
So first, she
enters her location.

00:11:39.410 --> 00:11:42.090
Then she says that she wants
to work in a supermarket.

00:11:42.090 --> 00:11:44.124
She specifies her
desired salary,

00:11:44.124 --> 00:11:45.540
and then she starts
getting a list

00:11:45.540 --> 00:11:46.984
of jobs matching her criteria.

00:11:46.984 --> 00:11:49.150
On average these jobs are
about four kilometers away

00:11:49.150 --> 00:11:51.950
from her home, so it's
a big improvement.

00:11:51.950 --> 00:11:53.420
Then she can
schedule an interview

00:11:53.420 --> 00:11:55.960
or share each different
job with a friend.

00:11:55.960 --> 00:11:58.805
She confirms her interview,
she is good to go.

00:11:58.805 --> 00:12:01.180
And Emprego Ligado had started
getting some great results

00:12:01.180 --> 00:12:02.800
from their SMS-only service.

00:12:02.800 --> 00:12:04.590
But you can see that
this process isn't

00:12:04.590 --> 00:12:09.220
quite as interactive or as easy
to use as you might want to be.

00:12:09.220 --> 00:12:10.500
So they saw another trend.

00:12:10.500 --> 00:12:13.290
Android was starting to take
off in Brazil, big time.

00:12:13.290 --> 00:12:15.560
And so they saw that this
was an opportunity for them

00:12:15.560 --> 00:12:18.150
to build a much more
engaging experience.

00:12:18.150 --> 00:12:20.320
So the app launched
in September 2014,

00:12:20.320 --> 00:12:22.760
with all the same goals
as the SMS service,

00:12:22.760 --> 00:12:24.660
but it's a lot more fun to use.

00:12:24.660 --> 00:12:27.230
And they saw that Android
users were actually a lot more

00:12:27.230 --> 00:12:28.850
engaged with the service, too.

00:12:28.850 --> 00:12:31.840
They were, in fact, applying
to about eight times more jobs

00:12:31.840 --> 00:12:34.120
than the average person
on the SMS service.

00:12:34.120 --> 00:12:35.590
And the jobs they
apply for tended

00:12:35.590 --> 00:12:38.305
to require more
technical skills, too.

00:12:38.305 --> 00:12:40.430
They also saw that the
people using the Android app

00:12:40.430 --> 00:12:43.030
were actually much younger on
average than the people using

00:12:43.030 --> 00:12:44.492
the SMS-only service.

00:12:44.492 --> 00:12:46.700
And that's pretty exciting,
because in Brazil there's

00:12:46.700 --> 00:12:49.630
actually a very popular
national apprenticeship program.

00:12:49.630 --> 00:12:51.962
That's a real big on-ramp
for a lot of young Brazilians

00:12:51.962 --> 00:12:53.920
to find a meaningful
career that will take them

00:12:53.920 --> 00:12:55.340
far in their lives.

00:12:55.340 --> 00:12:58.800
And now they're doing this with
Emprego Ligado to help them.

00:12:58.800 --> 00:13:02.480
So far, they've had
a significant impact.

00:13:02.480 --> 00:13:05.750
They've had over a million
users through both their SMS

00:13:05.750 --> 00:13:07.580
and their Android app services.

00:13:07.580 --> 00:13:10.370
And they've been able to
match about 8 million jobs

00:13:10.370 --> 00:13:12.360
to their users search criteria.

00:13:12.360 --> 00:13:15.290
And think about what that
would do if that was you.

00:13:15.290 --> 00:13:17.909
If your commute time got
reduced by that much,

00:13:17.909 --> 00:13:19.450
not only would you
feel more relaxed,

00:13:19.450 --> 00:13:20.914
you'd have time
with your family.

00:13:20.914 --> 00:13:22.830
But maybe you could even
walk or bike to work,

00:13:22.830 --> 00:13:26.660
and that would have a big
impact on your health too.

00:13:26.660 --> 00:13:29.259
And then it also had a
big impact on employers.

00:13:29.259 --> 00:13:30.800
We talked earlier
about the struggles

00:13:30.800 --> 00:13:32.671
that employers would
have with recruitment.

00:13:32.671 --> 00:13:35.170
And now it's really helped them
reduce their training costs,

00:13:35.170 --> 00:13:37.000
because they're able
to find employees who

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:38.920
have more relevant experience.

00:13:38.920 --> 00:13:40.760
And because the commute
times are better,

00:13:40.760 --> 00:13:43.800
they're no longer losing so many
employees due to the traffic

00:13:43.800 --> 00:13:46.110
problems and the transit time.

00:13:46.110 --> 00:13:47.910
And so this is
how Emprego Ligado

00:13:47.910 --> 00:13:50.370
is using their disruptive
job matching algorithms

00:13:50.370 --> 00:13:53.250
to save millions of dollars
for Brazilian companies

00:13:53.250 --> 00:13:57.930
every year on retention
and employee recruitment.

00:13:57.930 --> 00:13:59.402
And Emprego Ligado
actually makes

00:13:59.402 --> 00:14:00.610
money providing this service.

00:14:00.610 --> 00:14:01.780
That's pretty awesome.

00:14:01.780 --> 00:14:04.310
And this has allowed them
to expand their own team.

00:14:04.310 --> 00:14:07.902
They've now grown to team 40,
and 36 of them are Brazilians.

00:14:07.902 --> 00:14:09.360
They get interviewed
on the TV news

00:14:09.360 --> 00:14:12.040
regularly about how they're
helping the traffic problem.

00:14:12.040 --> 00:14:16.260
They're actually taking
crowded buses off the roads.

00:14:16.260 --> 00:14:18.360
So let's go back to Fernanda.

00:14:18.360 --> 00:14:21.790
So with Emprego Ligado, she was
able to find a new job really

00:14:21.790 --> 00:14:22.427
quickly.

00:14:22.427 --> 00:14:24.760
And it was a job that she was
really well qualified for.

00:14:24.760 --> 00:14:26.750
And it was much
closer to her home.

00:14:26.750 --> 00:14:28.660
So with this extra time
she was able to save,

00:14:28.660 --> 00:14:30.570
she could spend more
time with her family,

00:14:30.570 --> 00:14:33.070
and really had an
improved quality of life.

00:14:33.070 --> 00:14:35.180
So here we have
how Emprego Ligado

00:14:35.180 --> 00:14:37.270
is making the Brazilian
job market work better

00:14:37.270 --> 00:14:38.510
for everybody.

00:14:38.510 --> 00:14:41.400
They're increasing access to
information for both employees

00:14:41.400 --> 00:14:43.085
and employers.

00:14:43.085 --> 00:14:45.210
Now we're going to move to
a totally different part

00:14:45.210 --> 00:14:47.420
of the world, and we're
going to talk about Flipkart

00:14:47.420 --> 00:14:49.120
in Bangalore, India.

00:14:49.120 --> 00:14:51.740
So has anyone here
used the Flipkart app?

00:14:51.740 --> 00:14:52.430
Yeah?

00:14:52.430 --> 00:14:53.540
Fantastic.

00:14:53.540 --> 00:14:55.409
Well, if you haven't
tried it before,

00:14:55.409 --> 00:14:57.700
I'll tell you a little bit
more about what you can buy.

00:14:57.700 --> 00:14:59.950
You could get basically
any type of product.

00:14:59.950 --> 00:15:02.020
You could get a lamp
for your living room,

00:15:02.020 --> 00:15:05.232
you could get a refrigerator,
you could get some new clothes.

00:15:05.232 --> 00:15:07.440
And actually, when I was
cruising around the Flipkart

00:15:07.440 --> 00:15:09.340
app, I learned about
a new type of product

00:15:09.340 --> 00:15:12.930
I'd never even heard of
before-- bike sleeves.

00:15:12.930 --> 00:15:14.390
Does any one know these?

00:15:14.390 --> 00:15:15.130
Yeah?

00:15:15.130 --> 00:15:16.080
These are awesome.

00:15:16.080 --> 00:15:17.500
So if you've never
heard of them,

00:15:17.500 --> 00:15:19.374
they're something that
you wear on your arms.

00:15:19.374 --> 00:15:20.900
They're kind of
like leg warmers,

00:15:20.900 --> 00:15:23.350
but you wear them when you're
riding your motorcycle.

00:15:23.350 --> 00:15:24.670
And if you want to--
you know, you're more

00:15:24.670 --> 00:15:26.760
a minimalist person, you
can choose a basic color

00:15:26.760 --> 00:15:27.805
like black or white.

00:15:27.805 --> 00:15:29.680
And then if you want to
go a little bit wild,

00:15:29.680 --> 00:15:32.630
you can choose these tattoo
printed bike sleeves over here

00:15:32.630 --> 00:15:33.500
on the right.

00:15:33.500 --> 00:15:35.760
And the reason that
Flipkart sells bike sleeves

00:15:35.760 --> 00:15:39.090
is that in India, motorcycles
are an extremely popular way

00:15:39.090 --> 00:15:40.250
to get around.

00:15:40.250 --> 00:15:43.560
Today we're seeing that in
India about two million cars,

00:15:43.560 --> 00:15:47.014
every month, are sold, but
about 12 million motorcycles.

00:15:47.014 --> 00:15:48.930
So having the right set
of products that meets

00:15:48.930 --> 00:15:52.310
the market's needs is really
key to Flipkart's growth.

00:15:52.310 --> 00:15:53.990
And their growth
has been enormous.

00:15:53.990 --> 00:15:56.530
As of March this year, they're
moving about $4 billion

00:15:56.530 --> 00:15:58.730
of merchandise
annually, and they're

00:15:58.730 --> 00:16:01.940
expecting it to double
by the end of the year.

00:16:01.940 --> 00:16:03.990
So where's this
growth coming from?

00:16:03.990 --> 00:16:06.390
It's coming from mobile.

00:16:06.390 --> 00:16:10.570
And the online shopping market
in India is growing huge.

00:16:10.570 --> 00:16:12.610
In 2016 there's
going to be about 100

00:16:12.610 --> 00:16:14.820
million online shoppers,
and the market's

00:16:14.820 --> 00:16:18.250
going to grow by about 50%
for the next four years.

00:16:18.250 --> 00:16:23.061
It's going to get up to
about $16 billion in 2018.

00:16:23.061 --> 00:16:25.560
And this was all made possible
because of the massive growth

00:16:25.560 --> 00:16:26.990
of smartphones.

00:16:26.990 --> 00:16:31.680
So next year in India the
number of smartphone users

00:16:31.680 --> 00:16:34.750
is actually going to be bigger
than the entire population

00:16:34.750 --> 00:16:36.390
of the United States.

00:16:36.390 --> 00:16:38.730
This is huge.

00:16:38.730 --> 00:16:40.770
And in India mobile
has gotten so popular

00:16:40.770 --> 00:16:43.364
that Flipkart's focusing
more and more on apps.

00:16:43.364 --> 00:16:44.780
They're making so
much more money.

00:16:44.780 --> 00:16:47.690
In fact, their Android app
has about 1.5x higher order

00:16:47.690 --> 00:16:49.880
frequency compared
to the desktop web.

00:16:49.880 --> 00:16:52.290
90% of their mobile
traffic is on Android.

00:16:52.290 --> 00:16:55.490
And so they've taken
the next logical step.

00:16:55.490 --> 00:16:57.400
They shut down their
mobile website.

00:16:57.400 --> 00:17:00.680
And they said, hey,
just go get our app.

00:17:00.680 --> 00:17:03.060
And their sister site,
Myntra, which is actually

00:17:03.060 --> 00:17:05.092
owned by Flipkart, took
it one step further,

00:17:05.092 --> 00:17:06.800
and on May first this
year, they actually

00:17:06.800 --> 00:17:09.180
shut down their
desktop website too.

00:17:09.180 --> 00:17:11.131
You just go there and
it says, get our app.

00:17:11.131 --> 00:17:13.089
And we're seeing a lot
of similar announcements

00:17:13.089 --> 00:17:15.240
across all sorts of
online retailers in India,

00:17:15.240 --> 00:17:18.484
because of this massive
growth in mobile.

00:17:18.484 --> 00:17:20.900
So one of the reasons that
Flipkart has been so successful

00:17:20.900 --> 00:17:22.880
is they know how to
market to people there.

00:17:22.880 --> 00:17:24.650
They know how to make
the right things.

00:17:24.650 --> 00:17:27.890
But they also know how to make
sense of logistical problems

00:17:27.890 --> 00:17:30.310
and how to solve them in a
local way that makes sense.

00:17:30.310 --> 00:17:33.265
So I found out about this
group of people recently.

00:17:33.265 --> 00:17:34.640
It's a whole
community of people,

00:17:34.640 --> 00:17:35.912
and here's what they do.

00:17:35.912 --> 00:17:37.370
If you're an office
worker, they go

00:17:37.370 --> 00:17:40.610
to your house in the morning,
they pick up a hot cooked lunch

00:17:40.610 --> 00:17:42.570
that someone in your
house has made for you,

00:17:42.570 --> 00:17:45.690
they deliver it to your desk
hot just in time for lunch.

00:17:45.690 --> 00:17:47.950
You eat your lunch, and then
they take your lunch box

00:17:47.950 --> 00:17:49.154
back home for you.

00:17:49.154 --> 00:17:50.570
And they're called
the dabbawalas,

00:17:50.570 --> 00:17:53.650
and they've been doing
this for about 120 years.

00:17:53.650 --> 00:17:55.850
In Mumbai, there's
about 5,000 dabbawalas,

00:17:55.850 --> 00:18:00.040
and they deliver about
200,000 lunches per day.

00:18:00.040 --> 00:18:00.710
It's amazing.

00:18:00.710 --> 00:18:02.220
And Flipkart recently
announced that they're

00:18:02.220 --> 00:18:03.845
going to be working
with the dabbawalas

00:18:03.845 --> 00:18:07.519
to do last mile delivery in
some of India's biggest cities.

00:18:07.519 --> 00:18:09.060
And the reason they
wanted to do this

00:18:09.060 --> 00:18:11.690
is that the dabbawalas
are basically awesome.

00:18:11.690 --> 00:18:14.660
They deliver tons of packages
with nearly zero errors.

00:18:14.660 --> 00:18:17.860
In fact, Harvard Business
School did a 2010 case study,

00:18:17.860 --> 00:18:20.280
and they compared the
accuracy of the dabbawalas

00:18:20.280 --> 00:18:21.780
to the Six Sigma process.

00:18:21.780 --> 00:18:23.420
And they said,
yup, it's basically

00:18:23.420 --> 00:18:26.700
meeting that same level of
reliability and service.

00:18:26.700 --> 00:18:28.920
And so we're seeing
here how Flipkart

00:18:28.920 --> 00:18:33.320
is combining new technologies
with local market insights

00:18:33.320 --> 00:18:36.000
to create a new market,
a new e-commerce market,

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:39.490
in one of the world's
biggest economies.

00:18:39.490 --> 00:18:41.210
So next we're going
to go to Europe.

00:18:41.210 --> 00:18:43.040
We're going to go to BlaBlaCar.

00:18:43.040 --> 00:18:44.730
And if you haven't
tried them yet,

00:18:44.730 --> 00:18:46.834
you should the next
time you're in Europe,

00:18:46.834 --> 00:18:49.500
or one of many other places that
we're going to talk about soon.

00:18:49.500 --> 00:18:52.740
They're the most successful long
distance ride sharing service.

00:18:52.740 --> 00:18:54.350
So when you sign
up for BlaBlaCar,

00:18:54.350 --> 00:18:56.420
you have to describe yourself.

00:18:56.420 --> 00:18:57.440
OK.

00:18:57.440 --> 00:18:59.300
Anyone else in the
audience a Bla?

00:18:59.300 --> 00:19:00.716
If you don't know
what that means,

00:19:00.716 --> 00:19:02.810
it means you don't like
to talk in the car.

00:19:02.810 --> 00:19:04.014
Just don't talk to me.

00:19:04.014 --> 00:19:05.430
Maybe you're like
me, and you like

00:19:05.430 --> 00:19:08.160
to talk a little bit,
but not the whole time.

00:19:08.160 --> 00:19:10.120
And then we probably all
know some in our life

00:19:10.120 --> 00:19:12.130
who we'd call a
BlaBlaBla, and that's

00:19:12.130 --> 00:19:15.020
someone who just talks non-stop.

00:19:15.020 --> 00:19:17.570
So why is this important?

00:19:17.570 --> 00:19:20.820
Well, if you are running a
hugely successful long distance

00:19:20.820 --> 00:19:23.550
ride sharing service
where the average trip is

00:19:23.550 --> 00:19:26.630
about 200 miles, you're
going to quickly learn

00:19:26.630 --> 00:19:29.650
that if you stick a
Bla and a BlaBlaBla

00:19:29.650 --> 00:19:33.160
together in a car
for 200 miles, you

00:19:33.160 --> 00:19:37.886
are going to have two
very unhappy customers.

00:19:37.886 --> 00:19:39.730
But, if you have this
algorithm and you

00:19:39.730 --> 00:19:42.230
know what questions
to ask, you'll

00:19:42.230 --> 00:19:45.220
know that you can just stick
two BlaBlaBlas together,

00:19:45.220 --> 00:19:48.760
and maybe you've built
a lifelong friendship.

00:19:48.760 --> 00:19:51.300
So let's talk about how
BlaBlaCar works with one

00:19:51.300 --> 00:19:52.950
of its most popular routes.

00:19:52.950 --> 00:19:55.240
Let's say that I'm a driver.

00:19:55.240 --> 00:19:57.250
I have my Renault.
I live in Paris

00:19:57.250 --> 00:19:59.940
and I'm going to go back to
my hometown of Rennes, where

00:19:59.940 --> 00:20:00.754
I grew up.

00:20:00.754 --> 00:20:02.170
Maybe it's for the
holidays, maybe

00:20:02.170 --> 00:20:04.485
I'm just making an
impromptu visit to a friend.

00:20:04.485 --> 00:20:07.110
And I'm actually going to spend
a lot of money on gas and tolls

00:20:07.110 --> 00:20:07.870
to get there.

00:20:07.870 --> 00:20:09.940
It's going to be a long drive.

00:20:09.940 --> 00:20:12.450
And in fact, the trip may be
so expensive that I can't even

00:20:12.450 --> 00:20:14.510
go as often as I'd like to.

00:20:14.510 --> 00:20:16.570
So I can just launch
the BlaBlaCar app,

00:20:16.570 --> 00:20:19.630
and it'll match me with other
people going the same way.

00:20:19.630 --> 00:20:21.390
I don't actually make
money doing this,

00:20:21.390 --> 00:20:24.920
but I can offset all of
my costs of gas and tolls.

00:20:24.920 --> 00:20:27.130
And I can sell the other
three seats in my Renault

00:20:27.130 --> 00:20:30.040
to three other people who
are going on the same trip.

00:20:30.040 --> 00:20:32.790
So this is a much
cheaper alternative.

00:20:32.790 --> 00:20:36.350
So a train ticket would cost
about three times as much.

00:20:36.350 --> 00:20:39.020
A plane ticket would cost
about six times as much.

00:20:39.020 --> 00:20:40.700
And if you've ever
had the experience

00:20:40.700 --> 00:20:43.140
of buying a train or
plane ticket at absolutely

00:20:43.140 --> 00:20:45.220
that last minute,
when it's so critical,

00:20:45.220 --> 00:20:48.400
you know that those
costs could be way more.

00:20:48.400 --> 00:20:51.090
So it's a good option to have.

00:20:51.090 --> 00:20:53.367
And this is the BlaBlaCar team.

00:20:53.367 --> 00:20:55.950
They're headquartered in Paris
and it sounds like a really fun

00:20:55.950 --> 00:20:56.942
place to work.

00:20:56.942 --> 00:20:58.650
One of my favorite
programs I heard about

00:20:58.650 --> 00:21:00.810
is called the BlaBla swap.

00:21:00.810 --> 00:21:03.380
So they have offices all
over the globe because they

00:21:03.380 --> 00:21:04.470
reach so many users.

00:21:04.470 --> 00:21:06.630
And if you do a BlaBla
swap, what you can do

00:21:06.630 --> 00:21:09.440
is go work in another
company's office for week.

