00:24:17.230 --> 00:24:19.190
So next up we have Dexcom.

00:24:19.190 --> 00:24:22.360
They're here too,
today, which is great.

00:24:22.360 --> 00:24:25.200
And they're making some of the
world's most advanced blood

00:24:25.200 --> 00:24:27.049
glucose monitoring technology.

00:24:27.049 --> 00:24:28.840
And their focused on
improving human health

00:24:28.840 --> 00:24:31.270
through innovation.

00:24:31.270 --> 00:24:33.500
So every time I look at
these stats on the screen,

00:24:33.500 --> 00:24:34.740
I get a little bit depressed.

00:24:34.740 --> 00:24:37.290
I've looked at them a few times.

00:24:37.290 --> 00:24:41.750
29 million Americans have
been diagnosed with diabetes.

00:24:41.750 --> 00:24:43.800
And when we say
diagnosed, that means

00:24:43.800 --> 00:24:46.650
that there's a lot more people
who have diabetes but are not

00:24:46.650 --> 00:24:49.040
diagnosed, or people who
are pre-diabetic and will

00:24:49.040 --> 00:24:50.890
become diagnosed soon.

00:24:50.890 --> 00:24:55.430
But even still, that 29 million
is 9.3% of the population.

00:24:55.430 --> 00:24:59.640
And worse, 200,000 of those
people are under age 20.

00:24:59.640 --> 00:25:02.610
It's also led to a
ridiculous amount of cost

00:25:02.610 --> 00:25:07.420
in terms of lost wages and
medical expenses in the US.

00:25:07.420 --> 00:25:10.740
So if you don't have diabetes
yet you should be happy.

00:25:10.740 --> 00:25:12.530
Because it's a lot of work.

00:25:12.530 --> 00:25:14.620
I have a few friends
who have diabetes,

00:25:14.620 --> 00:25:16.245
and when they're
going through a period

00:25:16.245 --> 00:25:18.820
where their diabetes is
getting difficult to control,

00:25:18.820 --> 00:25:22.330
they have to test their
blood sugar all the time,

00:25:22.330 --> 00:25:25.430
and that could mean
before meals, a few times

00:25:25.430 --> 00:25:28.420
after a meal, before
and after exercise,

00:25:28.420 --> 00:25:31.080
in the middle of the night,
any time they don't feel well.

00:25:31.080 --> 00:25:33.455
And they have to make sure
that their blood sugar doesn't

00:25:33.455 --> 00:25:36.470
get too high, and it
doesn't get too low either.

00:25:36.470 --> 00:25:38.220
And then the information
that you get back

00:25:38.220 --> 00:25:41.750
from a typical blood glucose
test is not very useful.

00:25:41.750 --> 00:25:43.840
What does 95 mean?

00:25:43.840 --> 00:25:46.000
What's going to happen
a half hour from now?

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:49.210
How do I know if 95 means that
I should eat some candy now,

00:25:49.210 --> 00:25:51.090
because my blood sugar's
about to go too low,

00:25:51.090 --> 00:25:52.881
or I should take some
insulin, because it's

00:25:52.881 --> 00:25:54.410
about to go too high?

00:25:54.410 --> 00:25:58.720
And one patient described this
to Dexcom as basically this.

00:25:58.720 --> 00:26:01.480
It's like I'm driving down
a winding road at night,

00:26:01.480 --> 00:26:04.490
and I only turn on the
headlights occasionally.

00:26:04.490 --> 00:26:07.290
That is scary, when your
life could depend on this.

00:26:07.290 --> 00:26:09.970
So the Dexcom team thought
that there must be a better way

00:26:09.970 --> 00:26:12.700
to be able to deal with this.

00:26:12.700 --> 00:26:15.350
So they've created this
continuous glucose monitor.

00:26:15.350 --> 00:26:17.960
And you wear it on your
body, as you can see here.

00:26:17.960 --> 00:26:21.180
So instead of pricking your
finger a few times every day,

00:26:21.180 --> 00:26:23.769
you just get this
continuous graph.

00:26:23.769 --> 00:26:26.060
Basically it does the equivalent
of checking your blood

00:26:26.060 --> 00:26:28.294
sugar every five
minutes, and it gives you

00:26:28.294 --> 00:26:30.460
the full picture of how
your blood sugar is reacting

00:26:30.460 --> 00:26:32.800
in terms of, you know,
you eat something,

00:26:32.800 --> 00:26:34.070
does it go up and down?

00:26:34.070 --> 00:26:36.590
You go and do some
exercise, how does it react?

00:26:36.590 --> 00:26:38.850
And this makes it easier
to monitor your diabetes

00:26:38.850 --> 00:26:41.070
and keep it under control.

00:26:41.070 --> 00:26:44.560
So does anyone here have anyone
in their family with diabetes?

00:26:44.560 --> 00:26:46.101
Maybe a friend?

00:26:46.101 --> 00:26:46.600
Yeah?

00:26:46.600 --> 00:26:47.141
A few people.

00:26:47.141 --> 00:26:47.970
I do.

00:26:47.970 --> 00:26:51.200
And so this can be
a scary experience

00:26:51.200 --> 00:26:53.810
that you have to manage,
especially if that person who

00:26:53.810 --> 00:26:56.520
has diabetes is a child.

00:26:56.520 --> 00:26:59.126
So Dexcom, next week-- we're
very excited about this--

00:26:59.126 --> 00:27:01.000
they're going to be
launching their companion

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:01.990
app on Google Play.

00:27:01.990 --> 00:27:04.410
So the whole idea
here is that a parent

00:27:04.410 --> 00:27:06.220
could use this app on
their Android phone

00:27:06.220 --> 00:27:07.830
to check on their
child's blood sugar.

00:27:07.830 --> 00:27:10.490
And they can even get alerts
if that blood sugar goes out

00:27:10.490 --> 00:27:12.066
of the safe range.

00:27:12.066 --> 00:27:13.440
And this is great
because parents

00:27:13.440 --> 00:27:15.060
don't have to buy
a separate device,

00:27:15.060 --> 00:27:16.070
or carry it around with them.

00:27:16.070 --> 00:27:18.030
They can just use their
existing Android phone

00:27:18.030 --> 00:27:21.110
to stay on top of
their kids health.

00:27:21.110 --> 00:27:23.190
And finally, we're
incredibly excited

00:27:23.190 --> 00:27:24.910
about a special
integration that Dexcom

00:27:24.910 --> 00:27:27.630
is doing with Android
Wear's latest technology.

